  "method": "We propose OV-RAD: an open-vocabulary region-align-and-detect pipeline that learns to localize and name objects without per-class box supervision. OV-RAD marries two components: (1) a word–region aligner pre-trained on image–caption pairs that grounds noun phrases to proposals through contrastive learning, and (2) a DETR-style query detector that predicts class-agnostic boxes and scores them by similarity to arbitrary text embeddings at inference. The vision backbone is a self-supervised ViT (e.g., DINO) to improve generalization under scarce labels. The text side is a Transformer encoder that embeds phrases, attributes, and compositional prompts into a shared space with image regions and boxes.\n\nPre-training proceeds under a unified formulation across three supervision sources. For raw web pairs, we parse noun phrases from captions, generate K proposals per image, and perform 1-to-1 max-similarity set alignment between phrases and proposals, optimizing a text-to-region contrastive loss. We focus contrast on text-relevant regions by selecting proposals with high similarity to any concept in the local batch. To strengthen fusion and boundary precision, we add cross-modal pretext tasks: masked language modeling conditioned on regions and masked region classification conditioned on text, projecting 5-D box geometry into the shared encoder so the model learns location-aware alignments. When grounding links are available (e.g., segmentations associated with phrases/questions), we supervise cross-attention maps to point to the correct evidence, transferring fine localization to the aligner.\n\nWe then train the detector as an open-vocabulary, set-prediction model. A Transformer decoder with N object queries predicts boxes via Hungarian matching using geometric costs; instead of a fixed softmax over classes, each query’s box token is scored by cosine similarity to text embeddings for an open phrase bank. We explicitly model negatives: unmatched proposals/queries are pushed away from all phrases (background) and we sample hard negative phrases from the same image/batch, which sharpens decision boundaries and reduces collapse to head concepts. Training alternates batches from detection-style data (seen classes) and web pairs, forming a flywheel between localization and recognition while avoiding reliance on per-class box labels for tail/novel classes.\n\nAt inference, OV-RAD supports two modes. For prompted detection, users provide a few descriptors (“red modular connector”, “two-wheeled transporter”) or high-level categories; we expand these with a question-guided captioner and compute relevance maps from cross-attention to sample high-signal patches, yielding diverse, phrase-specific cues. The detector computes similarity between query boxes and all phrase embeddings and returns boxes with novelty-aware calibration (temperature-scaled cosine, energy-based background thresholding). For unprompted discovery, we output class-agnostic boxes ranked by objectness, cluster their region embeddings over the dataset to propose new categories, and optionally backfill names by nearest-phrase retrieval or post-hoc human labeling. A lightweight self-training loop on target images refines box localization using high-confidence pseudo groundings without per-class labels.",
  "rationale": "The core failure on long-tail and novel objects stems from reliance on per-class box supervision and closed-vocabulary classifiers. By learning fine-grained word–region alignment directly from image–text pairs and scoring detections by similarity to arbitrary phrases, OV-RAD decouples localization from fixed labels and inherits open-vocabulary recognition. A set-prediction detector eliminates NMS heuristics and produces non-duplicated boxes that can be matched to text post-hoc, while explicit background/hard-negative training calibrates against head-class bias and tightens boundaries.\n\nQuestion-guided patch selection and caption expansion reduce search over the image and phrase space, improving recall on rare concepts with minimal or no examples. Using a DINO-style backbone and cross-modal geometry-aware pretext tasks further regularizes the model under scarce labels, while alternating training on detection-style and web data bootstraps localization without per-class supervision. Together, these choices enable detection and localization of long-tail and novel objects, with or without user-provided names.",
