  "method": "We propose ReLENT: Region-level Entailment and Novel Term Expansion for open-vocabulary object discovery. ReLENT decouples objectness from naming and replaces cosine-similarity classification with a triadic, region-level vision–language NLI head trained under weak and structured supervision. A class-agnostic set-prediction detector first proposes K regions using a ViT backbone with a DETR-style decoder trained only for objectness and box regression. Each region feature r and a candidate phrase p are fed to a cross-attentional NLI head that outputs entail/contradict/unknown probabilities. To regularize semantic granularity without per-class boxes, the NLI head is multi-resolution: alongside the fine phrase decision, it jointly predicts hypernym categories and attribute tokens derived from lexical resources, with consistency constraints between levels.\n\nSupervision is constructed from image–text corpora without per-class boxes by combining multiple weak signals. From captions, we extract noun/attribute phrases via SRL and form image-level entailment labels; we generate counterfactual negatives by semantically controlled perturbations (e.g., role-swaps, attribute flips) that remain fluent but are false for the image. We train the NLI head with multiple-instance learning: for entailed phrases, at least one region must entail; for negatives, all regions should contradict. To sharpen boundaries and reduce spurious matches, we adopt token-by-token negative supervision: for each region, we sample many non-evidential tokens and phrases and explicitly teach the model to assign the ‘contradict’ label, while BIO-style masking around high-heat patches enforces tighter spatial support. Where available, we transfer grounding from QA-linked segmentation data by converting linked segmentations into positive region–phrase entail examples and hard negatives from non-linked but nearby segments; this anchors the MIL objective with sparse, precise supervision. A multi-resolution auxiliary loss enforces that if a fine phrase entails a region, its hypernyms and key attributes also entail, providing structured regularization across label granularities.\n\nTo name long-tail and novel objects, ReLENT performs retrieval-augmented vocabulary expansion on-the-fly. Given an image (and optionally high-confidence coarse hypernyms from the NLI head), we build a text query from pooled region descriptors and retrieve a diverse set of candidate phrases and definitions from a large FAISS index of noun/attribute strings and KB synsets. Each candidate’s retrieval score is discretized into confidence bins and embedded as an additional signal in the text encoder, allowing the NLI head to contextually modulate its decisions by source reliability. The retrieved candidates are then scored by the region-level NLI head to produce entailment maps; for phrases that entail without mapping to any known taxonomy, we output them directly or assemble descriptive names by composing top-entailed attributes.\n\nTo actively surface novel concepts with minimal passes, we maintain a small ensemble of phrase-proposer policies (particles) that, conditioned on current region features and NLI posteriors, each selects a batch of next phrases to test from the index. The particles are trained with a Bayesian objective to maximize expected information gain—i.e., reduction in uncertainty over region–phrase entailment—regularized to a broad prior so they explore different semantic neighborhoods. We approximate this posterior over policies with SVGD, where policy gradients push particles toward high-gain strategies while a kernel repulsion term preserves diversity. At inference, ReLENT alternates between (1) proposing regions, (2) retrieving and proposing phrases, (3) evaluating with the NLI head, and (4) updating a per-image belief state until a budget is reached. The final detections are boxes whose fine phrases entail and whose hypernym and attribute heads are consistent; when no name cleanly entails, we return attribute-rich descriptions and mark them as novel.",
  "rationale": "ReLENT avoids per-class box supervision and the well-trodden word–region cosine classification by reframing open-vocabulary detection as region-level entailment with structured weak supervision and retrieval. The MIL-trained NLI head uses only image-level captions plus counterfactual negatives and sparse QA-grounded anchors to learn to localize textual evidence, which naturally transfers to unseen categories. Retrieval-augmented term expansion equips the model with a dynamic, image-conditional vocabulary far beyond any fixed label set, while embedding retrieval confidence stabilizes decisions under noise. The multi-resolution heads regularize semantics via hypernyms and attributes, improving generalization on long-tail classes where fine labels are rare but coarse categories and attributes are common.\n\nThe active, SVGD-based phrase proposer maximizes information gain over the NLI outputs and maintains diverse querying strategies, allowing the system to discover and name novel objects efficiently without exhaustive scoring of a massive vocabulary. Token-by-token negative supervision and sparse QA-grounding improve boundary fidelity and reduce over-acceptance—key failure modes when labels are scarce—yielding a detector that can detect and localize rare or novel objects through entailment rather than per-class supervision.",
