  "method": "We propose OPEN-PRO (Open-world Prototype- and pROmpt-adapted detector), a two-branch detector that localizes objects class-agnostically and assigns semantics without per-class supervision by combining (i) a class-agnostic localization head trained from self-supervised objectness, (ii) a prototype-driven semantic head with single-pass uncertainty for open-set handling, and (iii) an uncertainty-guided, visual-prompt adaptation loop for continual domain shift and long-tail discovery. The backbone is shared, but the neck and heads are specialized: one head optimizes geometry/objectness, the other learns a discriminative latent space with prototypes and an uncertainty readout. At inference, OPEN-PRO outputs high-recall boxes for all objects; regions that align with existing prototypes are labeled accordingly, while high-objectness but high-uncertainty regions are flagged as novel and still localized.\n\nStage A (bootstrap objectness and geometry): Train a class-agnostic detector (e.g., RPN/center-based head) to maximize recall using self-supervised region discovery and invariance, without per-class labels. Use proposal mining from saliency/edges and view-invariant contrastive learning on cropped regions to form positives, with background regions as negatives; optimize localization (IoU/L1/GIoU) and an objectness score. This yields a strong “thingness” prior and well-calibrated boxes independent of class supervision.\n\nStage B (semantic prototypes with uncertainty): Attach a latent discriminant module before the classification logits that maps each region feature to a prototype-similarity vector via a bank of trainable prototypes. Train the semantic head with an instance-discrimination/NCA-style objective so that discovered regions form tight clusters around prototypes, while an auxiliary uncertainty head regresses confidence directly from the discriminant embedding. This single-pass uncertainty gates learning and inference: if a region is high-objectness but far from all prototypes (low max-similarity/high uncertainty), it is treated as unknown; otherwise, it is softly assigned to its nearest prototype. To prevent entanglement between geometry and semantics, split the region representation into two latents: a shared, class-agnostic geometry/objectness channel that only feeds the localization head, and a class-specific semantic channel regularized by a separate prior that feeds the prototype head.\n\nStage C (novel-class discovery without labels): Run OPEN-PRO on unlabeled images, select regions with high objectness and high uncertainty, and cluster them (e.g., agglomerative/DBSCAN in the discriminant space) to propose pseudo-classes. Instantiate new prototypes at cluster centroids and fine-tune the semantic head using uncertainty-weighted pseudo-labels: confident cluster members contribute more, outliers are down-weighted or ignored. Merge or split prototypes based on inter-prototype similarity and stability across epochs. This loop grows a prototype vocabulary for novel classes entirely from unlabeled data while maintaining high-recall localization. If a few labeled exemplars arrive later, they simply seed or refine corresponding prototypes without altering the objectness head.\n\nStage D (uncertainty-guided prompt adaptation for long-tail shift): Insert lightweight, pixel-level visual prompts at the backbone input to adapt features to new domains/classes on the fly. Maintain an EMA teacher of the full model; on streaming unlabeled data, update only the prompts (and optionally the semantic prototypes) using teacher pseudo-boxes and prototype assignments, with update magnitudes modulated by sample uncertainty (larger updates for uncertain samples where adaptation is most needed). This keeps bandwidth/compute low and mitigates catastrophic forgetting. During inference, report: (1) localized detections aligned to existing prototypes (known or previously discovered) and (2) localized “novel object” findings where uncertainty remains high despite strong objectness, enabling immediate deployment in open-world settings without per-class supervision.",
  "rationale": "Long-tail and novel classes are hard because per-class supervision is missing precisely where we need it. OPEN-PRO addresses this by decoupling localization from semantics: a class-agnostic objectness/geometry head ensures we still localize any object, while a prototype-based semantic head equipped with single-pass uncertainty flags when a region is far from all known prototypes. This turns the absence of labels into a discovery signal: high-objectness, high-uncertainty regions become candidates for new classes and are organized via clustering into pseudo-classes that continually expand the model’s vocabulary without needing annotations.\n\nRare classes also correlate with domain shift (new appearances, contexts). Lightweight visual prompts adapted with an uncertainty-guided EMA let the backbone absorb new low-level statistics and features most where the model is unsure, improving recall and stability under continual change while avoiding full-model drift. Factorizing the representation into class-agnostic and class-specific channels prevents the localization skill from being perturbed by evolving semantics. Together, these components detect and localize novel or long-tail objects immediately, then self-organize them into stable prototypes over time—without per-class supervision and with graceful integration of any eventual few-shot labels.",
